Big O notation.

Big O notation describes how an algorithm's runtime or memory usage grows relative to the size of its input. The input size is conventionally called n.

There are three things to internalise about Big O. First, it describes growth, not absolute speed. An algorithm that scales well might still be slower than a simpler one for very small inputs — Big O tells you what happens as n gets large.

Second, it drops constants and lower-order terms. Three n plus one hundred, and plain n, are both linear time. At large scale, the three and the hundred become irrelevant compared to the n.

Third, it usually describes the worst case — the upper bound, the most demanding scenario your algorithm might encounter.
